1270":"1185–1270","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1220–1275":"1220–1275","1250–1301":"1250–1301","–Male":"Overleden","1160–1245":"1160–1245","1164–Female":"1164–Overleden","1215":"1215","Abt 1245":"circa 1245","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1160":"1160","England.":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stainsby, Bolsover district, Derbyshire, England":"Bolsover, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bolsover, Derbyshire, England":"Bolsover, Derbyshire, England","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"1185–1270":"1185–1270","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1220–1275":"1220–1275","1250–1301":"1250–1301","–Male":"Deceased","1160–1245":"1160–1245","1164–Female":"1164–Deceased","1215":"1215","Abt 1245":"about 1245","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1160":"1160","England.":"England, United Kingdom","Stainsby, Bolsover district, Derbyshire, England":"Bolsover, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Bolsover, Derbyshire, England":"Bolsover, Derbyshire, England","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Saint","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Andries","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Auguste, Gabrielle, Leonce.","Flemish and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Andries</i>, a vernacular form of   Andreas  . The Flemish surname is also found in France (Nord)."],"variants":[{"name":"Dries","meanings":["Dutch and German: from the personal name <i>Dries</i>, a short form of   Andries  .","Dutch: variant of <b>Van den Dries</b>, a topographic name from <i>dries</i> ‘common meadow, not of good quality’."]},{"name":"Andreas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Heinz, Otto, Beate, Bernd, Ernst, Ilse, Kurt.","German and English: from the New Testament Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, which gave rise to   Andrew   in English and vernacular derivatives in almost every other European language. Etymologically, it is from Greek <i>andreios</i> ‘manly’, an adjective derivative of <i>anēr</i> (genitive <i>andros</i>) ‘man, male’. This is a Greek translation of an unknown Aramaic original; it was the name of the first of Christ's disciples, the patron saint of both Scotland and Russia. The Scottish surname   Anderson   is far more common than its Russian equivalent, <b>Andreev</b>. The personal name was popular throughout Europe in various vernacular forms (including Italian <i>Andrea</i>, French <i>André</i>, Spanish <i>Andrés</i>, Scottish, North German, and Scandinavian <i>Anders</i>, Dutch <i>Andries</i>, Hungarian <i>András</i>, Czech <i>Ondřej</i>, Polish <i>Andrzej</i> and <i>Jędrzej</i>, and Russian <i>Andrey</i>).","Americanized or Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Andrejaš</b>: from an old vernacular form of the personal name <i>Andraž</i> (from Latin <i>Andreas</i>), which is a variant of <i>Andrej</i>; see   Andrew  ."]}]},{"name":"Agatha","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Good, kind"],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agatha Saint Andries was born in 1185, in Bolsover, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Baron Henry William St. Andries, was 26 and her mother, Amanda Stanram, was 22. She married John Savage in 1215, in Bolsover, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1270, in her hometown, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1185–1270":"1185–1270","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1220–1275":"1220–1275","1250–1301":"1250–1301","–Male":"Surnud","1160–1245":"1160–1245","1164–Female":"1164–Surnud","1215":"1215","Abt 1245":"umbes 1245","1301":"1301","1245":"1245","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1160":"1160","England.":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stainsby, Bolsover district, Derbyshire, England":"Bolsover, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bolsover, Derbyshire, England":"Bolsover, Derbyshire, England","Staine